JOHANNESBURG - Transnet said on Friday that it would lift its force majeure declaration on Monday. ALSO READ:- Transnet cyberattack a massive setback that's causing logjams, losses - SAAFF- Transnet cyberattack could've been prevented if adequate defences taken - expert This was declared by the port terminals operating division at the container terminals in the ports of Cape Town, Durban, Ngqura and Port Elizabeth. The declaration of the force majeure took effect from Thursday after Transnet experienced a cyberattack, necessitating those operations be conducted manually. Spokesperson Ayanda Shezi said: “We are continuing to engage with our customers in terms of where we are and we would like to thank them for collaborating with us following the events of the past week.” Download the Eyewitness News app to your iOS  or Android device.